Why program at all?

  1. You understand more deeply what computers do to your data. By understanding the workings of an algorithm, you can better justify your claims as well as understand the ways algorithms may distort the data.
  2. The work of data analysis becomes transparent. Since were writing code, we can trace the steps we made to make something.
  3. We start to correct for the problem of tools shaping research questions. In other words, we build the tool to fit our questions.

Thanks to J. Heppler and L. Mullen for the wording.

Why R?

  1. Lots of libraries (ways of extending R language).
  2. The language is designed for data analysis.
  3. R has a set of tools available that makes writing code easier.
  4. Lots of humanists use R.
  5. Reproducibility.

Tidyverse

tidyverse is a set of packages for data tidying, manipulation, and visualization. Well look specifically at dplyr (manipulation) and ggplot2 (visualization) today. Their creator, Hadley Wickham, introduced the innovation of a human-friendly (at least for Westerners), left-to-right syntax. With ggplot, Wickham adapted Leland Wilkinsons Grammar of Graphics (1999) for the modular construction of graphs.

More on tidyverse? See Grolemund, Garrett, and Hadley Wickham. R for Data Science. Sebastopol, CA: OReilly Media, 2017. http://r4ds.had.co.nz/.

Tidy Data

Tidy data, according to Wickham, features:

  • Variables in columns
  • Observations in rows
  • Each table corresponds to a type of observational unit

Tidy data is easier to manipulate and visualize, allowing you to focus on the interesting questions, as opposed to the less interesting logistics of data.

Wickham, Hadley. Tidy Data. Journal of Statistical Software 59, no. 10 (September 12, 2014): 123. http://dx.doi.org/10.18637/jss.v059.i10.

Plotting Population Data

An unsurprising plot.

The Grammar of Graphics

Lets have a look at the code from that plot.

ggplot(data = oregon, aes(x = year, y = population)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

Semantic Components

Lets break that code down line-by-line.

ggplot(data = oregon, aes(x = year, y = population)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

ggplot() needs:

  1. mapping of data
  2. to aesthetic attributes
  3. using geometric objects
  4. with data statistically transformed
  5. and, if needed, mapped onto a facet or coordinate system

Semantic Components (2)

data: data as an R data frame

geoms: describe the geometric objects that represent data, such as points, lines, and polygons.

aesthetics: describe visual characteristics that represent data, such as position, size, color, and shape.

stats: describe statistical transformations such as counts, means, medians, or regression lines.

[]

ggplot() Function Call

Lets review what we did with the ggplot() code. The code for our previous bar chart looked like:

ggplot(data = oregon, aes(x = year, y = population)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

Mapping of data:

data = oregon

to aesthetic attributes:

aes(x = year, y = population)

using geometric objects:

geom_bar(stat="identity")

ggplot() Function Call (2)

See the geom_bar documentation for the differences in the stat flag. By default, geom_bar uses stat='count' which sets the height of the bar proportion to the number of cases in each group. Since we want the height of the bars to represent values in the data, we use stat='identity' to map a variable to the y aesthetic.

Web Graphics

With htmlwidgets and shiny, it is also possible to create interactive visualizations and host them on the web. htmlwidgets creates R bindings for some well-known JavaScript libraries, like sigma.js and networkD3.

Resources

I find the R Graph Catalog to be particularly helpful when deciding which kind of graph is appropriate for my data. The site is a realization in the R language of the lessons presented in Robbins, Naomi R. Creating More Effective Graphs. Wayne, NJ: Chart House, 2013.

While there are countless books on coding in R, I find myself returning to these resources again and again: Jenny Bryans stat545 class and Jason Hepplers and Lincoln Mullens class on R and Data Visualization in the Humanities.
